The Politics of Mask Use During COVID-19¶

Benedicte Knudson, Diego Oldenburg, Alex Abadi Final Data Science Tutorial CMPS 3160-01 - Introduction to Data Science

Notebook

Project description and goals From the very beginning of the pandemic, mask use has been highly politicized. We are interested in finding out the effects of the politicization and seeing if mask use is truly as decisive an issue as the media has made it out to be. To accomplish this, we will attempt to answer the following questions:

  1. How does self-reported mask use vary across each county in the United States?

  2. How does self-reported mask use in each county in the US correlate with how they voted in the 2020 presidential election?

Collaboration plan To begin, we have set up a GitHub repository and a Google colab document that we all have access to where we will store and update our code. We will be meeting weekly as a group and have committed to doing work individually on our own time.

Extract, Transform, Load¶

Data description The New York Times has a number of incredibly robust data sets relating to COVID-19. We will be using specifically their data sets about face mask use and total COVID-19 cases and deaths. (A note about the face mask use data: the data was collected over a period of about two weeks, during July 2020. The data is self reported from around 250,000 people. We understand that self reported data must be taken with a grain of salt.) The data about the 2020 election at the county level has been provided by a GitHub user tonmcg, 2020 election results at the county-level are scraped from results published by from Fox News, Politico, and the New York Times. To help create the the choropleth county maps, we used TIGER/Line Shapefiles provided by Census.gov.

Tidying data To tidy the data, we will:

  1. Drop unused columns
  2. Replace incorrect or empty values with NaNs
  3. Convert data to appropiate types
  4. Rename, organize columns

mask_df We will be using all the variables in mask_df. We can check the dtype of the data frame to see if any variables are objects when they shouldn't be, and if so, convert them to the correct type.

In [8]:
mask_df.dtypes
Out[8]:

SOMETIMES     float64
FREQUENTLY    float64

dtype: object

The dtypes all seem correct, no incorrect or empty values. The final step will be renaming the columns (using rename) so they match the syntax of the other columns. COUNTYFP will be changed to county_fips, so it is synchronous with the column in election_df so it will be easier to combine later on.

In [9]:
mask_df=mask_df.rename({"COUNTYFP":"county_fips"}, axis=1)
mask_df=mask_df.rename({"NEVER":"Never"}, axis=1)
mask_df=mask_df.rename({"RARELY":"Rarely"}, axis=1)
mask_df=mask_df.rename({"SOMETIMES":"Sometimes"}, axis=1)
mask_df=mask_df.rename({"FREQUENTLY":"Frequently"}, axis=1)
mask_df=mask_df.rename({"ALWAYS":"Always"}, axis=1)

Next, looking at the dtypes, we see that the states, county, city, and college columns are all objects, which is fine. The two case columns are ints and floats. Since we might end up dropping them, we will leave them for now.

election_df Finally, let's look at election_df. It is extremely convenient that the county_fips data is formatted the same way in both election_df and mask_df. This will provide an easy link between the tables. We will want to drop a few columns we don't intend to use and drop "County" from each entry in the county_name column to create an easy link to colleges_df. To isolate the first word in county_name, we'll use a regex to replace " County" with "" (nothing).

Graph 1: A histogram using the data from mask_df to understand what mask use looks like country-wide. Each stack along the X axis represents a state. The FIPS codes go in alphabetical order by county by state, so they are represented in the graph alphabetically. The states with thickest lines have more counties.

Graph 3: These two graphs visualize the the difference between two self reported mask use options, Never and Always, between people who voted Democrat vs. Republican. You may notice they are symmetrical. The per_gop data is the inverse of the per_dem, which accounts for the symmetry.</br> The 'Never wears mask by political party' graph shows the same thing, the more a county votes red, the less likely they are to always wear a mask.

Model Questions¶

The analysis brings up an important relation that can be described using statistical modeling. We are going to do a statistical analysis to find the correlation between the percent of people that answered 'never' when asked if they wear masks and the county's dominant political affiliation based on the 2020 presidential election.

Using SKLearn's linear regression model to predict the percentage of registered democrats in a hypothetical county where 100% of people reportedly never wear a mask.

In [42]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

X_train = masks_elections[["Always", "Never"]]
y_train = masks_elections["per_dem_x"]

scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(X_train)
X_train_sc = scaler.transform(X_train)

regressor = LinearRegression()
regressor.fit(X_train_sc, y_train)

x_new = pd.DataFrame()
x_new["Always"] = [0.0]
x_new["Never"] = [1.0]


x_new_sc = scaler.transform(x_new)

regressor.predict(x_new_sc)

Conclusions¶

Our regression models showed a number of things: 1. There would be no Democrat voters in county where everyone self-reported not wearing a mask. 2. Conversely, there would only be Republican voters in a county where everyone self-reported not wearing a mask. 3. In a hypotheical county where 100% of people reportedly wear a mask, only slightly above 60% of them would be Democratic voters.

We can now answer our initial questions:

  1. How does self-reported mask use vary across each county in the United States? Mask use, despite our prediction, is quite even across the US. Around 80% of the population, according to the self reported data, always or frequently wear masks. While this might have changed since the time the data was collected, this does show that masks were not a politicized as we may have been lead to believe.

  2. How does self-reported mask use in each county in the US correlate with how they voted in the 2020 presidential election? Mask use was generally accepted by most counties in the US, but our analysis showed that counties with a higher rate of never and rarely wearing mask were more likely to be counties that voted for the Republican presidential candidate in the 2020 election.

Knowing that we are far from the end of the pandemic, it is reassuring knowing that a good portion of the country would mask up when the time calls for it. (The time is now.)
